%h2 Semantic Markup With Sass
%p Like the previous examples, you also have the following mixins to create your own classes. By using this mixins you to don't have to put the <code>.brand</code> class.
.docs-code
  :code
    # lang: scss
    // @param {string} $name - Typography style name
    @include typography($name);
%p You can use our mixins to use the brand typographt on your own markup, like this one:
.docs-example.bg-white
  .docs-example-type.columns.one-columns
    .column
      %p.my-metadata &hearts; 17 de Febrero de 2015 &nbsp;&nbsp; &hearts; hace 10 minutos
      %p.my-title Sed posuere consectetur est at lobortis.
      %p.my-lead Donec sed odio dui. Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam. Nullam id dolor id nibh ultricies vehicula ut id elit. Maecenas sed diam eget risus varius blandit sit amet non magna. Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam.
      %p.my-body Aenean lacinia bibendum nulla sed consectetur. Sed posuere consectetur est at lobortis. Vivamus sagittis lacus vel augue laoreet rutrum faucibus dolor auctor. Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam. Maecenas faucibus mollis interdum. Cras justo odio, dapibus ac facilisis in, egestas eget quam. Duis mollis, est non commodo luctus, nisi erat porttitor ligula, eget lacinia odio sem nec elit. Vestibulum id ligula porta felis euismod semper. Morbi leo risus, porta ac consectetur ac, vestibulum at eros. Morbi leo risus, porta ac consectetur ac, vestibulum at eros. Fusce dapibus, tellus ac cursus commodo, tortor mauris condimentum nibh, ut fermentum massa justo sit amet risus.
.docs-code.join
  :code
    # lang: scss
    // In your stylesheet
    .my-metadata { @include typography(caption); }
    .my-title    { @include typography(display3); }
    .my-lead     { @include typography(lead); }
    .my-body     { @include typography(body); }
  :code
    # lang: html
    <!-- In your HTML -->
    <h1 class="my-title"> ... </h1>
    <p class="my-metadata hint"> ... </h1>
    <p class="my-lead"> ... </h1>
    <p class="my-body"> ... </h1>
%p Also you can do of this way:
.docs-code.join
  :code
    # lang: scss
    // In your stylesheet
    span { @include typography(caption); }
    h1   { @include typography(display1); }
    h3   { @include typography(lead); }
    p    { @include typography(body); }
  :code
